NAME
    insert_bulk - bulk insert records from JSON array

SYNOPSIS
    insert_bulk <path> [--file=<file>] [--dry-run]
    cat data.json | insert_bulk <path>

DESCRIPTION
    Inserts multiple records efficiently using a single API call.
    Input must be a JSON array of record objects.

    Unlike insert, this command:
    - Does NOT accept key=value pairs
    - Requires JSON array input (not single objects)
    - Uses direct API for better performance
    - Is designed for imports and batch operations

OPTIONS
    --file=<path>
        Read JSON from file instead of stdin.

    --dry-run
        Validate input without inserting. Reports how many
        records would be inserted.

EXAMPLES
    cat users.json | insert_bulk /api/data/users
        Bulk insert from piped JSON

    insert_bulk /api/data/products --file=products.json
        Insert from file

    insert_bulk /api/data/orders --dry-run < orders.json
        Validate without inserting

    curl -s https://example.com/data.json | insert_bulk /api/data/items
        Insert from remote source

INPUT FORMAT
    Input must be a JSON array of objects:

    [
      {"name": "Alice", "email": "alice@example.com"},
      {"name": "Bob", "email": "bob@example.com"}
    ]

    Records may include "id" field, or IDs will be generated.

OUTPUT
    On success: "Inserted N records into <model>"
    On dry-run: "Dry run: would insert N records into <model>"

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success
    1   Error (invalid JSON, API error, etc.)

SEE ALSO
    insert, update, delete, select, dump, restore
